WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.150 --> 00:00:06.900
All right, so last time we
began, or maybe two times ago,

00:00:06.900 --> 00:00:11.154
we began a discussion of
various vocabulary and facts you

00:00:11.154 --> 00:00:15.408
have to know about the markets
if you want to think about

00:00:15.408 --> 00:00:16.320
finance.
 

00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:19.395
Today we're going to deal
mostly with the most important

00:00:19.395 --> 00:00:21.800
one, the most basic one,
the yield curve.

00:00:21.800 --> 00:00:23.523
And last time,
we introduced this word,

00:00:23.523 --> 00:00:24.430
"yield."
 

00:00:24.430 --> 00:00:29.564
Now, yield is an extremely
common expression in finance,

00:00:29.564 --> 00:00:33.672
and it turns out not to be that
well defined,

00:00:33.672 --> 00:00:36.100
often, or that useful.
 

00:00:36.100 --> 00:00:39.566
But the word is so important
and has been used so often that

00:00:39.566 --> 00:00:42.503
it still hangs around,
even when probably we should

00:00:42.503 --> 00:00:44.090
use different concepts.
 

00:00:44.090 --> 00:00:48.360
So remember the yield was an
attempt to look at an

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:50.520
investment,
and without paying any

00:00:50.520 --> 00:00:53.130
attention to the market or
anything outside the investment,

00:00:53.130 --> 00:00:55.160
just looking at the investment
itself,

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:57.989
try to assess,
give a number,

00:00:57.989 --> 00:01:02.840
quantifying how attractive the
investment was.

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:06.159
So we said you could apply that
to a bond--it has cash flows.

00:01:06.159 --> 00:01:08.912
You could apply it to a hedge
fund that's taking in money and

00:01:08.912 --> 00:01:13.293
paying out money,
and the formula we came up with

00:01:13.293 --> 00:01:18.659
said that if the cash flows are
given by C(1),

00:01:18.659 --> 00:01:24.093
C(2), the net cash flows,
C(T) over the course of the

00:01:24.093 --> 00:01:27.918
period,
and its price is some P(0),

00:01:27.918 --> 00:01:31.420
maybe it's a negative cash
flow,

00:01:31.420 --> 00:01:32.688
so C(0).
 

00:01:32.688 --> 00:01:34.861
So some of these cash flows
might be negative and some of

00:01:34.861 --> 00:01:38.459
them might be positive,
then we should just look at the

00:01:38.459 --> 00:01:43.703
number Y,
such that discounting all these

00:01:43.703 --> 00:01:47.890
things at rate Y gives you 0.
 

00:01:47.890 --> 00:01:51.786
The Y that did that was what we
defined as the yield of the

00:01:51.786 --> 00:01:52.660
investment.
 

00:01:52.660 --> 00:01:54.530
So we saw that that had some
advantages.

00:01:54.530 --> 00:01:56.041
For example,
in a hedge fund,

00:01:56.041 --> 00:01:59.226
if you just look at the rate of
return it makes on its money

00:01:59.226 --> 00:02:01.566
every year,
that doesn't take into account

00:02:01.566 --> 00:02:03.718
that in some years,
it's got a lot more money.

00:02:03.718 --> 00:02:05.739
So if those were the years that
lost money,

00:02:05.739 --> 00:02:08.082
and the years when it hardly
had any money were the years it

00:02:08.082 --> 00:02:09.992
made money,
just taking the average,

00:02:09.992 --> 00:02:13.324
the multiplicative average,
the geometric average of all

00:02:13.324 --> 00:02:16.810
those yearly rates of returns,
would give a misleading figure.

00:02:16.810 --> 00:02:19.598
Well, the yield also gives a
somewhat misleading figure,

00:02:19.598 --> 00:02:24.456
and I don't want to spend too
much time on why it might be

00:02:24.456 --> 00:02:27.686
misleading,
but I'll give you just an

00:02:27.686 --> 00:02:28.419
example.
 

00:02:28.419 --> 00:02:34.074
Suppose that the cash flows
happen to be 1,

00:02:34.074 --> 00:02:35.690
-4, and 3.
 

00:02:35.690 --> 00:02:37.919
Now what's the yield to
maturity?

00:02:37.919 --> 00:02:40.710
Well, there are two of them.
 

00:02:40.710 --> 00:02:46.580
You could have Y = 0,
because 1 over (1 0),

00:02:46.580 --> 00:02:50.494
- 4 over (1 0),
3 over (1 0),

00:02:50.494 --> 00:02:53.288
is just 1 - 4 3.
 

00:02:53.288 --> 00:02:57.042
That equals 0,
so the yield to maturity of 0

00:02:57.042 --> 00:03:02.366
percent, the yield of 0 percent,
makes this have present value

00:03:02.366 --> 00:03:02.889
0.
 

00:03:02.889 --> 00:03:08.389
But also I could try Y = 200
percent,

00:03:08.389 --> 00:03:14.210
and then I'd have Y--I'd put a
2 and a 2 squared here,

00:03:14.210 --> 00:03:23.909
and I'd have 1 - 4 thirds 1
over 3 squared is 3 over 9,

00:03:23.909 --> 00:03:25.090
so it's 1 third.
 

00:03:25.090 --> 00:03:28.394
So it would be 1 minus 4
thirds, plus 1 third,

00:03:28.394 --> 00:03:30.008
which also equals 0.
 

00:03:30.008 --> 00:03:33.235
So is the yield to maturity,
the internal rate of return 0

00:03:33.235 --> 00:03:34.650
percent or 200 percent?
 

00:03:34.650 --> 00:03:36.080
It's ambiguous.
 

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:39.818
So yield to maturity can't be
the right way of doing things.

00:03:39.818 --> 00:03:41.680
To go back to the hedge fund
example,

00:03:41.680 --> 00:03:44.699
you know, the hedge fund was
taking in money,

00:03:44.699 --> 00:03:46.830
paying out money,
taking in more money,

00:03:46.830 --> 00:03:50.264
paying out money,
and we calculated the yield to

00:03:50.264 --> 00:03:51.068
maturity.
 

00:03:51.068 --> 00:03:53.710
Well suppose that there was
some period,

00:03:53.710 --> 00:03:55.750
you know, here,
at which point everyone had

00:03:55.750 --> 00:03:58.247
taken all their money out,
so the hedge fund wasn't

00:03:58.247 --> 00:04:00.378
actually doing anything for a
bunch of years,

00:04:00.378 --> 00:04:03.246
maybe for a long time,
and then it started up and took

00:04:03.246 --> 00:04:05.408
money in and paid money out and
stuff.

00:04:05.408 --> 00:04:08.062
Well, because the gap in time
was very long with nothing

00:04:08.062 --> 00:04:09.996
happening,
if you take a positive Y,

00:04:09.996 --> 00:04:13.080
the stuff that happens in the
second incarnation of the fund

00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:15.590
is hardly going to be making any
difference,

00:04:15.590 --> 00:04:18.043
because by that time,
it will all be discounted a

00:04:18.043 --> 00:04:18.350
lot.
 

00:04:18.350 --> 00:04:23.947
So the yield will depend too
sensitively on stuff early

00:04:23.947 --> 00:04:26.540
rather than stuff late.
 

00:04:26.540 --> 00:04:30.028
And so again,
you get into troubles yielding

00:04:30.028 --> 00:04:33.160
just yield to maturity,
so that can't be the right

00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:35.923
thing to do,
even though people have done it

00:04:35.923 --> 00:04:36.709
for years.
 

00:04:36.709 --> 00:04:38.271
So the word,
however, lives on,

00:04:38.271 --> 00:04:41.293
and there's no getting rid of
the word because it's used in

00:04:41.293 --> 00:04:42.440
common vocabulary.
 

00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:44.529
Now what would Irving Fisher
say you should do,

00:04:44.529 --> 00:04:46.940
if you had to summarize how
good an investment was?

00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:48.509
What's his lesson?
 

00:04:48.509 --> 00:04:50.889
What do you do?
 

00:04:50.889 --> 00:04:55.370
An investment where there's no
doubt about what the cash flows

00:04:55.370 --> 00:04:58.603
are going to be,
what would he say you should

00:04:58.603 --> 00:05:01.910
do, to evaluate the
attractiveness of it?

00:05:01.910 --> 00:05:03.892
What's our lesson,
our main lesson from Irving

00:05:03.892 --> 00:05:04.290
Fisher?
 

00:05:04.290 --> 00:05:06.459
What would he say?
 

00:05:06.459 --> 00:05:07.050
Yes.
 

00:05:07.050 --> 00:05:08.228
Student:
&gt;

00:05:08.228 --> 00:05:08.699
like to check?
 

00:05:08.699 --> 00:05:11.211
Prof: Well,
let's say they're cash flows,

00:05:11.211 --> 00:05:13.307
so it's money,
money that you're going to get

00:05:13.307 --> 00:05:15.495
coming in and out,
yeah, he'd say,

00:05:15.495 --> 00:05:21.175
deflate by inflation and turn
them into real flows and then do

00:05:21.175 --> 00:05:21.920
what?
 

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:23.149
So just continue your answer.
 

00:05:23.149 --> 00:05:26.788
So turn them into actual
potatoes every time,

00:05:26.788 --> 00:05:28.360
apples each time.
 

00:05:28.360 --> 00:05:37.959
Deflate by inflation and then
do what with the numbers?

00:05:37.959 --> 00:05:38.839
This is a simple question.
 

00:05:38.839 --> 00:05:41.560
You're thinking too hard.
 

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:42.230
Yes?
 

00:05:42.230 --> 00:05:43.649
Student:
Compare the present value.

00:05:43.649 --> 00:05:45.024
Prof: Okay,
he'd say, "Just look at

00:05:45.024 --> 00:05:46.399
the present value of all these
things."

00:05:46.399 --> 00:05:48.553
So of course,
to do that, you'd have to know,

00:05:48.553 --> 00:05:51.293
what is the market rate of
interest with which to compute

00:05:51.293 --> 00:05:52.370
the present value?
 

00:05:52.370 --> 00:05:54.656
So Fisher would say,
"It's ridiculous to

00:05:54.656 --> 00:05:57.826
evaluate how good an investment
opportunity is just by looking

00:05:57.826 --> 00:05:58.970
at the cash flows.
 

00:05:58.970 --> 00:06:00.920
You're throwing away too much
information."

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:03.406
You know what the market is
doing, you know what the

00:06:03.406 --> 00:06:04.430
interest rates are.
 

00:06:04.430 --> 00:06:09.338
Use the market interest rates
and figure out what the present

00:06:09.338 --> 00:06:12.040
value of all the cash flows is.
 

00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:15.473
So we're going to now do that a
bunch of times,

00:06:15.473 --> 00:06:19.879
okay, for the rest of the
class, and see what that means.

00:06:19.879 --> 00:06:23.673
So we have to begin,
the two thirds of the class is

00:06:23.673 --> 00:06:27.771
going to be spent on the
question, how do you know what

00:06:27.771 --> 00:06:30.579
the market rates of interest
are?

00:06:30.579 --> 00:06:32.639
So how do you know what the
market rates of interest are?

00:06:32.639 --> 00:06:36.170
How could you find out what the
market rate of interest is?

00:06:36.170 --> 00:06:38.839
What would you do to find it
out?

00:06:38.839 --> 00:06:39.550
Yeah.
 

00:06:39.550 --> 00:06:41.920
Student:
You could go to a bank and see

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:43.870
what they were estimating it to
be.

00:06:43.870 --> 00:06:45.509
Prof: And if you looked
in the newspaper,

00:06:45.509 --> 00:06:47.009
say, could you find it in the
newspapers?

00:06:47.009 --> 00:06:48.649
What would you find in the
newspapers?

00:06:48.649 --> 00:06:49.279
Yes?
 

00:06:49.279 --> 00:06:51.954
Student:
You'd want to find a riskless

00:06:51.954 --> 00:06:53.899
investment, say like a T-bill.
 

00:06:53.899 --> 00:06:57.499
Prof: Okay,
and so yes, you try and look at

00:06:57.499 --> 00:07:01.329
riskless investments like
government bonds,

00:07:01.329 --> 00:07:03.730
where there can't be any
default--at least,

00:07:03.730 --> 00:07:05.019
that's what they always used to
say--

00:07:05.019 --> 00:07:09.379
can't be any default on an
American promise.

00:07:09.379 --> 00:07:12.767
America's government never
broke a promise and they can

00:07:12.767 --> 00:07:15.507
always print the money,
so presumably they don't have

00:07:15.507 --> 00:07:17.399
to break a promise--
so they're just promising money

00:07:17.399 --> 00:07:19.247
which they can print,
so why should they ever break

00:07:19.247 --> 00:07:22.038
their promise--
so what would you find if you

00:07:22.038 --> 00:07:23.569
opened a newspaper?
 

00:07:23.569 --> 00:07:27.639
You would find,
for different maturities--

00:07:27.639 --> 00:07:30.389
it used to be up to 30
years--for different maturities,

00:07:30.389 --> 00:07:38.069
you would find the yield on the
various bonds,

00:07:38.069 --> 00:07:38.519
okay?
 

00:07:38.519 --> 00:07:41.940
So why would you find the yield?
 

00:07:41.940 --> 00:07:47.149
Well, the yield of various
government bonds,

00:07:47.149 --> 00:07:48.240
of gov.
 

00:07:48.240 --> 00:07:50.050
bonds.
 

00:07:50.050 --> 00:07:51.370
Why do they quote the yield?
 

00:07:51.370 --> 00:07:54.079
Well, that's just because,
you know,

00:07:54.079 --> 00:07:58.303
a hundred years ago,
people started using the idea

00:07:58.303 --> 00:08:02.439
of yield and so the vocabulary
has been kept,

00:08:02.439 --> 00:08:06.173
even though it's not the best
way of describing what's going

00:08:06.173 --> 00:08:06.490
on.
 

00:08:06.490 --> 00:08:10.005
So for instance,
let's just look at some of the

00:08:10.005 --> 00:08:14.134
yield curves you might have seen
over the last 9 years,

00:08:14.134 --> 00:08:17.269
almost 10 years,
since December 2000.

00:08:17.269 --> 00:08:23.129
You would see that in December
2000, the yield on the 1-year

00:08:23.129 --> 00:08:27.697
bonds, you know,
the short yields--this isn't a

00:08:27.697 --> 00:08:31.670
log scale, so this is 3,6,
12, okay.

00:08:31.670 --> 00:08:35.148
So the shortest bonds usually
have lower yields than the

00:08:35.148 --> 00:08:36.918
highest bonds,
but sometimes,

00:08:36.918 --> 00:08:40.144
like in December 2000,
the yields are almost all the

00:08:40.144 --> 00:08:40.840
same.
 

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:42.928
It's called the flat yield
curve.

00:08:42.928 --> 00:08:46.937
Other times,
like now, we're in this light

00:08:46.937 --> 00:08:51.500
blue one here,
right now the short bonds have

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:57.590
